A worker came to fix the kitchen floor, and I pretended to be working from home, but in reality, I was editing "Driven to Distraction."
I just wish this damned file could open. (OneDrive is absolutely useless.)
*The Hacker's Voice* I'm in.
He started drilling, and the sound was super loud. Great!
I set the air purifier to its maximum setting, which felt a bit too aggressive, but I really did smell sawdust, so it was justified, especially since he opposed wearing a mask. Plus, I do need to protect myself, don't I?
I really want to go back to sleep, but I can't sleep until he leaves.
The good news is that Chapter Four is finally edited!
Chapter five is really long and makes me super anxious. Yay! It's so exciting!
Replacing... ➡️ ellipsis, there are 54 😅 in this chapter.
But I still insist on this point. Most natural languages are incoherent, especially when people are emotionally excited.
The floor repairman is vacuuming, hoping that this means he's about to finish.
He went out (sounds like he's cutting something). I took a sneaky peek at the progress. There's still a lot of work to do :(
Chapter five still has seven pages left. This is still my favorite chapter, and the manuscript is in pretty good shape—mainly some formatting adjustments and minor changes to active voice and conciseness. But I really need a break, to have a cup of tea, while that guy is still busy in my kitchen.
He started using the vacuum cleaner again. I hope this is a good sign.
The worker repairing the kitchen floor has left!
He told me that he quoted the repair cost for the entire floor, but the landlord was too stingy and only agreed to cover the repair of the rotten area by the entrance. It feels much better now.
I was drinking tea in the garden, while the air purifier in the kitchen was working hard to purify the air in the room!
